An executive summary of the research is as follows:

"Urban flooding is a frequent occurrence in Ghana which has severe consequences for human health and wellbeing, as well as threatening economic development at micro and macro levels. The reasons for this are complex, including climate variability and climate change, as well as a lack of proper planning, inadequate waste management, and insufficient drainage. However, the hydrological and anthropogenic factors which contribute to flood risk in Ghana’s cities are poorly understood. The lack of high-resolution topographic data for Ghanaian cities is a major bottleneck to quantifying and understanding urban flood risk in the region. This project will use Pleiades-1B 0.5m panchromatic tri-stereo images from the ESA archive to generate high-resolution digital surface and elevation models for three cities in Ghana. The DEM will be supplied to an urban flood model in order to calculate inundation maps for the study areas, considering fluvial and pluvial flood processes. The resulting dataset will be used in further analyses to gain insight into the nature of flood risk in the study areas in particular, and Ghanaian cities in general."

